<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mission Viejo is Orange County's fasting growing city, according to county 
statistics. Its population increased 11.8%, from 75,241 in 1992 to 84,087 in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
 Another fast-growing city is Laguna Niguel, where the population increased 
5.2% (from 50,157 to 52,552), according to the Orange County Progress Report. 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim lost the most residents. Its population dropped 7.4% during the same 
period, from 279,124 to 258,477. 
</P>
<P>
 But Mission Viejo may not hold that distinction for long. A state report 
projects that population growth in the city will slow considerably in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
 Today 
</P>
<P>
 Details of the proposed North Irvine High School will be unveiled at a 
community meeting from 7 to 8 p.m. at the Woodbridge Community Church, 5000 
Barranca Parkway. 
</P>
<P>
 Architects from the Blurock Partnership will review the project along with 
school district facilities planner Corinne Loskot. 
</P>
<P>
 An opportunity for public comment will follow the presentation. 
</P>
<P>
 School officials want to build the campus in the Northwood area, one of the 
fastest growing villages in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call (714) 651-0444, Ext. 326. 
</P>
</TEXT>
