</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: AIRLINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 USAir, Union Officials Meet for Talks: Chairman Seth E. Schofield and 
President Frank Salizzoni of the Arlington, Va.-based carrier, along with top 
executives from British Airways -- which owns 24% of USAir -- and union leaders 
gathered in New York over the weekend for meetings, USAir spokesman David 
Shipley said.They were working on details of a plan to cut $500 million in 
labor costs, but Shipley declined to comment on the status of the talks. USAir 
has lost more than $2.6 billion in the last four years, and Schofield said in 
June that the company must cut $1 billion from its budget each year to survive 
competition from low-cost carriers. The talks had moved slowly until the crash 
Sept. 8 of USAir Flight 427 near Pittsburgh, Pa. According to the Washington 
Post, the crash jolted the unions to start working out internal differences in 
their approach to the talks. Federal investigators are still trying to 
determine the cause of the crash, which killed all 132 on board. A little more 
than two months before, a USAir jet crashed near Charlotte, N.C., killing 37 of 
57 people on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
