<TEXT>
<P>
 Health Products Survey Finds Worrisome Symptoms: Signs of slight financial 
ills emerged in an industry group's survey of leading health products makers, 
including giants Merck & Co. and Johnson & Johnson. The 1993 survey of 16 major 
companies in New Jersey, which has the nation's heaviest concentration of 
health care businesses, found modest declines in domestic sales, more companies 
cutting research expenditures, and layoffs after years of job growth. The 
industry in its report blamed managed health care and its pressure on drug 
prices, higher taxes, bigger rebates to government agencies and a recently 
imposed $100,000 fee for federal review of new drugs. 
